    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-cou1-nse",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error is scoped out for this assessment because the FEA model employs an implicit direct sparse solver (Ansys Sparse Direct) operating in the linear-elastic regime for the primary QoIs (stiffness and yield force). Implicit direct solvers for linear static problems do not accumulate iterative solver error in the sense addressed by ASME V&V 40 Factor 4; the dominant numerical error source is discretization error (Factor 3), which is separately and thoroughly assessed. The nonlinear post-yield displacement (force at 40 mm) uses a Newton-Raphson scheme with tight convergence tolerances (force residual < 0.1%), and solver convergence is verified at every load step. No iterative solver divergence or tolerance sensitivity was observed across the ensemble of 11 model runs. Scoping out this factor is consistent with ASME V&V 40-2018 Section 5.3.4 guidance that factors may be excluded when they are demonstrably not a significant contributor to total model uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-cou1-ue",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Use error is scoped out because the FEA models were constructed and executed exclusively by the original modeling team (FDA/CDRH computational scientists and DePuy Synthes FEA engineers) under a controlled, documented workflow with mandatory peer review at each modeling step. The simulation pipeline is scripted end-to-end using APDL macros under version control (Git SHA recorded in model provenance), eliminating manual data-entry steps that are the primary source of use error in ad-hoc analyses. A documented independent model review was completed prior to validation runs, confirming boundary conditions, material assignments, and contact definitions against the pre-registered simulation plan. Under these conditions, use error is not a plausible significant uncertainty contributor, and scoping it out is consistent with ASME V&V 40-2018 Section 5.3.4."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/factor/nagaraja-cou1-mf",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/nagaraja-cou1-mf-ac",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Model form acceptance criteria — continuum mechanics justification",
        "description": "Linear elastic continuum mechanics with isotropic Ti-6Al-4V material justified by literature; contact formulation validated against analytical Hertz solution. Required Gradation 3; achieved Gradation 3."
      },
      "rationale": "The choice of linear-elastic isotropic continuum mechanics for Ti-6Al-4V is well-supported by published material characterization data (elastic modulus 114 GPa, Poisson's ratio 0.34) and is standard practice for metallic implant FEA per FDA guidance. The augmented Lagrangian frictional contact formulation (μ=0.2 at screw-rod interface) was validated against an analytical Hertz contact solution to within 3%. Model form uncertainty is bounded by the validation comparison itself; all three QoIs fall within acceptance bounds, confirming model form adequacy at Gradation 3."
    },
    {
